      <description>&lt;h3 id=&#34;how-tchibos-themenwelten-became-scalable&#34;&gt;How Tchibo&amp;rsquo;s &amp;ldquo;Themenwelten&amp;rdquo; became scalable&lt;/h3&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;In the 1850s, coffee became popular among the general population. All social classes – rich and poor – drank the aromatic beverage. During the periods of crisis in the two World Wars, there was a decline in consumption.&lt;br&gt;&#xA;After World War II ended, coffee became a symbol for reconstruction and economic miracle. Drinking coffee meant being able to afford luxury goods.&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;At that time in 1949 Max Herz had an idea: Making coffee accessible to everyone again. And he made his vision become reality. In the same year he founded his coffee mailing business Tchibo together with his business partner Carl Tchiling. This revolutionized the coffee industry in just a few years.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
